The '''Hatun Kotama Flute School''' is part of a larger cultural center in the community of Kotama in [[Otavalo (city)|Otavalo]], [[Ecuador]]. The purpose of the center is to educate others about the world view and cultural expression of the Kotama community.<ref name=elnorte>{{cite news |first=Tupac |last=Lema |title=Las flautas de Kotama sonaron en EEUU |url=http://www.elnorte.ec/otavalo/actualidad/39034-las-flautas-de-kotama-sonaron-en-eeuu.html |work=El Norte |date=16 July 2013 |accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> Members of the school practice and teach traditional ''gaita'' music. The music is inspired by a deep connection with nature and the sounds that occur in everyday life, primarily utilizing the transverse flute, harmonica, and shells for instrumentation.<ref name=book>{{cite book |last1=Cachiguango |first1=Luis Enrique |first2=Julián |last2=Pontón| title=Yaku-Mama: La Crianza del Agua; La Música Ritual del Hatun Puncha – Inti Raymi en Kotama, Otavalo. |year=2010 |publisher= Ministerio de Cultura del Ecuador|location= Quito |isbn=9789942029317 |page=64}}</ref>
== History == The school was founded in the early 2000s by Luis Enrique Cachiguango under the name "The Village of Kotama's First Native Indigenous Flute School." Later in August 2008 the school was reinitiated under the name Hatun Kotama Flute School.<ref name=Liner>{{cite web|last=M. Vallejo|first=Jessie|title=Smithsonian Folkways Recordings|url=http://media.smithsonianfolkways.org/liner_notes/smithsonian_folkways/SFW40564.pdf|work=¡Así Kotama! The Flutes of Otavalo, Ecuador|accessdate=10 July 2013}}</ref> During the yearly celebration of inti-Raymi, the music plays a prominent role in community rituals and celebrations.
As part of the One World Many Voices program, Hatun Kotama performed at the 2013 [[Smithsonian Folklife Festival]] in Washington, D.C.<ref name=FOE>{{cite web|title=Friends of Ecuador|url=http://www.friendsofecuador.org/2013/06/ecuadorian-music-featured-at-dc-smithsonian-folklife-festival-july-3-7-2013/|work=Friends of Ecuador|accessdate=10 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Smithsonian Folklife Festival|url=http://www.festival.si.edu/2013/kashnami-kawsanchik-this-is-how-we-live/|accessdate=10 July 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130719140452/http://www.festival.si.edu/2013/kashnami-kawsanchik-this-is-how-we-live/|archivedate=19 July 2013|df=}}</ref> The performance also coincided with their second album ''¡Así Kotama! The Flutes of Otavalo Ecuador'' released on [[Smithsonian Folkways]].<ref name=Folksite>{{cite web|title=Smithsonian Folkways Recordings|url=http://www.folkways.si.edu/hatun-kotama/asi-kotama-the-flutes-of-otavalo-ecuador/latin-world-american-indian/album/smithsonian|work=Smithsonian Folkways|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>
