{{Infobox church |name = St Matthew's Church, Langford |fullname = Parish Church of St Matthew, Langford |image = Langford StMatthew SE.JPG
|style = [[Anglo-Saxon architecture|Anglo-Saxon]], [[Norman architecture|Norman]], [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]], [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] and [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] | years built = |caption = |denomination = [[Church of England]] |country = United Kingdom |coordinates = {{Coord|51|43|33.6|N|1|38|34.8|W|display=title}}
|vicar = Harry Campbell MacInnes | location = Langford, Oxfordshire GL7 3LG |website = |former name = |parish = Langford St Matthew, including Grafton and Radcot, Langford |deanery = Witney |archdeaconry = Oxford |diocese = [[Diocese of Oxford|Oxford]] |province = [[Province of Canterbury|Canterbury]] |founded date = |founder = |dedication = [[Matthew the Evangelist|Saint Matthew]] |earlydedication = [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Saint Mary]] |dedicated date = |consecrated date = |cult = |relics = |events = |past bishop = |people = |embedded={{Designation list| embed=yes | designation1 = Grade I Listed Building | designation1_offname = Church of St Matthew | designation1_date = 12 September 1955 | designation1_number = 1053385}} }}
The '''Parish Church of Saint Matthew, Langford''' is the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Langford, Oxfordshire|Langford]], a village in [[West Oxfordshire]] about {{convert|3|mi|0}} northeast of [[Lechlade]] in neighbouring [[Gloucestershire]].
==Government== The church was established as a chapelry of the [[Minster (church)#Early and Mid Anglo-Saxon periods|Anglo-Saxon minster]] of [[Bampton, Oxfordshire#Parish church|St. Mary's, Bampton]]. Later in the [[Anglo-Saxon England|Anglo-Saxon era]] Langford was elevated to a minster with its own dependent chapels at [[Grafton, Oxfordshire|Grafton]] and [[Radcot Bridge|Radcot]]. Both chapels are long gone, but Grafton and Radcot hamlets remain parts of Langford's [[ecclesiastical parish]].{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=3}}
Langford was part of the [[Diocese of Lincoln]] until the [[Diocese of Oxford]] was established under [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] in 1541. Despite becoming part of the new diocese, Langford remained a [[Prebendary#History|prebend]] of [[Lincoln Cathedral]] until 1848, when the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners Act 1840]] ceded all prebendal estates in England to the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners]].{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=6}}
The church at Langford was formerly dedicated to [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|St. Mary]]. It was later rededicated to its current patron, [[Matthew the Evangelist|St. Matthew]].{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=6}}
The parish is now part of the [[Benefice#Church of England|Benefice]] of Shill Valley and Broadshire, which includes also the parishes of [[Alvescot]], [[Black Bourton]], [[Broadwell, Oxfordshire|Broadwell]], [[Broughton Poggs]], [[Filkins]], [[Holwell, Oxfordshire|Holwell]], [[Kelmscott]], [[Kencot, Oxfordshire|Kencot]], [[Little Faringdon]], [[Shilton, Oxfordshire|Shilton]] and [[Westwell, Oxfordshire|Westwell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achurchnearyou.com/benefice.php?B=27/441BF |title=Benefice of Shill Valley and Broadshire |author=[[Archbishops' Council]] |publisher=[[Church of England]] |year=2010 |accessdate=28 June 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226072306/http://www.achurchnearyou.com/benefice.php?B=27%2F441BF |archivedate=26 December 2012 |df= }}</ref>
==Anglo-Saxon building== [[File:Langford StMatthew Crucifix.JPG|thumb|Headless rood of Christ, possibly 8th century, on east wall of south porch]] [[File:Langford StMatthew rood.JPG|thumb|10th century rood of Christ, St. Mary and St. John on south gable of south porch]] [[File:Langford StMatthew TowerDetail.JPG|thumb|11th century lancet windows and relief on the south wall of the tower]] The oldest parts of the present church at Langford are the [[bell tower]] and [[nave]], which were built in the second half of the 11th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|pp=678–679}} They may post-date the [[Norman conquest of England]], but they are very high quality work by Anglo-Saxon masons{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=679}} and are the most important Anglo-Saxon remains in Oxfordshire.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}}
The north and south [[Aisle#Architecture|aisles]] were added in about 1200 and the south porch in the 13th century, all in the [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] style.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=679}} The west walls of the nave and two aisles each have a 13th-century [[lancet window]].{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}} At one time the porch had two storeys. The upper storey has since been removed, but its blocked doorway and the outline of its stairs are still visible inside the south aisle.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}}
The porch includes two [[Anglo-Saxon art|Anglo-Saxon]] stone [[Rood#Crucifix or cross|rood]] reliefs, but they are repositioned and their original sites are not known. The one on the east wall of the porch is 8th century{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=8}} and has lost its head.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=681}} The one on the south gable of the porch is 10th century{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=7}} and has been assembled with [[Jesus Christ|Christ's]] left and right arms swapped over and the figures of [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Saint Mary]] and Saint [[John the Evangelist]] also transposed.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}}
==Later additions== In the 13th century the [[chancel]] was rebuilt wider and taller.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}} The line of the former 11th century Anglo-Saxon roof against the east wall of the tower can be seen at the west end of the chancel. The concave [[lozenge]] at the top of each of the chancel windows is a highly unusual feature for the 13th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}} The elaborate [[aumbry]] in the north wall of the chancel, with six compartments under three gables, is also unusual{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}} and suggests that it was a rich parish at the time.{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=5}}
Most of the windows of the north wall of the north aisle and south wall of the south aisle are 14th or 15th century [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] or [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] additions.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}} The present [[Baptismal font|font]] is 15th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=681}}
In 1574 two [[flying buttress]]es were added to the north side of the north aisle. The more westerly of the two bears an inscription giving the date in the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]]. A pair of tall, cylindrical pinnacles at the west end of the nave, surmounting the late Norman [[pilaster]] buttresses on the west gable wall, were also added in the 16th century.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}}
The pulpit is [[Jacobean architecture|Jacobean]],{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=681}} made in 1673.{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=7}} A clock was installed in the latter part of the 17th century{{sfn|Beeson|Simcock|1989|p=45}} but is now a static exhibit in the south aisle.
==Restoration and conservation== The architect and builder [[Richard Pace (Lechlade)|Richard Pace]] restored the building in 1829.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}} Further repairs were recommended by the [[Ecclesiastical Commissioners]]' surveyor [[Benjamin Ferrey]] in 1848 and undertaken the following year.{{sfn|Cotterill|2008|p=8}} The [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival architect]] [[Ewan Christian]] [[Victorian restoration|restored]] the nave roof to its original pitch in 1864.{{sfn|Sherwood|Pevsner|1974|p=680}}
St. Matthew's is now a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade I listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1053385 |desc=Church of St Matthew |date= |accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref>
==Bells== The [[Bell tower|tower]] has a [[Change ringing|ring]] of six bells.<ref name=DovesDetails>{{cite web |url=http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=Langford&DoveID=LANGFORD+O |title=Langford S Matthew |last=Davies |first=Peter |date=5 April 2007 |work=Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |accessdate=8 November 2010}}</ref> Four were cast in 1741 by Henry III Bagley of [[Chacombe#Social and economic history|Chacombe]], [[Northamptonshire]],<ref name=DovesDetails/> who at the time had a [[Bellfounding|bell-foundry]] at [[Witney]].<ref name=DovesFounders>{{cite web |url=http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/founders.php |title=Bell Founders |author=Dovemaster |date=25 June 2010 |work=Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |accessdate=8 November 2010}}</ref> The tenor and treble bells were cast by the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] in 1953.<ref name=DovesDetails/>
