[[File:The Font, Church of St. Lawrence, Thornton Curtis - geograph.org.uk - 1523590.jpg|thumb|300px|right|St Lawrence's, [[Thornton Curtis]], Lincolnshire.]]
[[File:Lion- carving on font, Lincoln.JPG|thumb|Detail from [[Lincoln Cathedral]].]]
[[File:Zedelgem - Fonts 2.JPG|thumb|Detail from the life of [[Saint Nicholas]], [[Zedelgem]].]]
[[File:Fonts.baptismaux.eglise.Montdidier.png|thumb|Drawing of the Montdidier font.]]
'''Tournai fonts''' are a type of [[baptismal font]] made from blue black [[limestone]] during the 12th and early 13th centuries in and around the Belgian town of [[Tournai]] by local masons.{{sfn|Drake (1999), p. 11}} There are seven complete examples in England{{sfn|Harris, p. 439}} and a disputed number in Europe: eighty according to one source,{{sfn|CRSBI, St Peter, Ipswich}} or fifty in Northern France and Belgium and two in Germany according to another.{{sfn|Wadsworth}}

A sculptural tradition, centred around Tournai, arose in the [[Scheldt]] valley from the 11th century onwards.{{sfn|Hourihane, p. 287}} This was characterised by its use of low [[relief]] (which was a useful feature when a sculpture was transported),{{sfn|Schwartzbaum, p. 90}} hard lines and the depiction of minute detail, these features arising from the hardness of the material used from the 12th century; Tournai marble.{{sfn|Hourihane, p. 287}} As a sculptural style it is distinguished from the contemporary style of [[Mosan art]], and it was used in sculpture in both [[Ghent]] and [[Bruges]].{{sfn|Hourihane, p. 287}} The designation "Tournai font" is employed to identify fonts made by local masons who worked the stone, as opposed to at least two other schools of masons who also sculpted the stone.{{sfn|Drake (1999), p. 11}}

==Construction==
The fonts are all sculpted from a single massive block{{sfn|Harris, p. 439}} of blue black [[Carboniferous Period|carboniferous]] limestone, known as "Tournai marble" (while not a true [[marble]], it was so called  as it is capable of taking a polish{{sfn|Drake (1999), p. 11}}), quarried from the banks of the River Scheldt. This seam of limestone runs from around [[Boulogne]] through the Scheldt and [[Meuse]] regions at [[Tournai]] and [[Namur]] to Aachen, and has been quarried and sculpted since [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] times.  One of these quarries, at [[Veldt-lès-Tournai]], is still in operation.{{sfn|Drake (1999), p. 11}} As a stone, Tournai marble was prized for its high polish, which made it appear black, and it was popular not only for fonts but also for elements of ecclesiastical architecture (capitals, bases and colonnettes), as well as for tombslabs.{{sfn|Schwartzbaum, p. 89}} 

Each font weighs approximately {{conv|2|tonne|ST kg lb}}{{sfn|Drake (1999), p. 11}} and was probably carved before transport;{{sfn|Tudor-Craig, p. 152}} this can be inferred not only from the fact that the stylistic elements (of people, flora and fauna) on all the fonts in England and the continent show a resemblance, and because the fonts themselves are all of the same shape,{{sfn|Schwartzbaum, p. 90}} but also because transport was difficult and expensive, and there would have been little point expending money and effort taking such heavy blocks to a distant site and then discarding up to half the block as waste material.{{sfn|Drake (1999), p. 11}} 

==Belgium, France and Germany==
[[File:Dendermonde OLV kerkbaptismal font 01.JPG|thumb|220px|right|Onze Lieve Vrouwekerk, [[Dendermonde]], Belgium.]]
[[File:Montdidier église St-Pierre (fonts baptismaux) 1.jpg|thumb|220px|right|St-Pierre de Montdidier, France.]]

===Complete fonts in churches===
The font at Onze Lieve Vrouwekerk, [[Dendermonde]] (Belgium) illustrates the story of [[Saint Peter]]'s denial of [[Jesus]].{{sfn|Wadsworth}} The font at [[Meise|Wolvertem]] (Belgium) is unusual in being round, square being the usual shape.{{sfn|Wadsworth}} There are also complete Tournai fonts in Blessy (France), [[Deftinge]] (Belgium), [[:fr:Deux-Acren|Deux-Acren]] (Belgium), [[Guarbecque]] (France), [[Hove, Belgium|Hove]] (Belgium), [[Lichtervelde]] (Belgium), [[:fr:Église Saint-Pierre de Montdidier|Montdidier]] (St Pierre) (France), [[:fr:Église Notre-Dame de La Neuville de Corbie|La Neuville-lès-Corbie]] (France), [[Noordpeene]] (France), [[Saint-Just-en-Chaussée]] (France), [[Vermand]] (France), [[Zedelgem]] (Belgium) and [[Zillebeke]] (Belgium).{{sfn|Drake (2010), Appendix 2 Belgium: Mosan and Tournai Fonts}}

====Bases and fragments====
Bases of Tournai fonts are in churches in [[Bourghelles]] (France), [[Évin-Malmaison]] (France), [[:fr:Froyennes|Froyennes]] (Belgium), [[Herentals]] (Belgium), [[Ichtegem]] (Belgium), [[Meilegem]] (Belgium), [[Ribemont]] (France), [[Roubaix]] (France) and [[St Sauveur]]{{dn|date=December 2017}}<!--[[:fr:Saint-Sauveur (Belgique)]]?-->.{{sfn|Drake (2010), Appendix 2 Belgium: Mosan and Tournai Fonts}}  There are fragments of Tournai fonts in churches in Baardegem, Comines, Ere, Escanaffles (building material), Lampernisse, Lessines (St Pierre) (building material), Nivelles and Soignies.{{sfn|Drake (2010), Appendix 2 Belgium: Mosan and Tournai Fonts}}

===In museums===
Complete fonts are at [[Châlons-sur-Marne]] (cathedral) and Gondecourt, a base at Pervijse, and fragments at Ghent (St Bavon), Kontich, and Rotselaer.{{sfn|Drake (2010), Appendix 2 Belgium: Mosan and Tournai Fonts}}

===Disputed examples===
Disputed examples of Tournai fonts are at Chéreng, [[Compiègne]] (St Antoine), Hautmont, and Laon (cathedral). The fragment at Le Tréport is also disputed.{{sfn|Drake (2010), Appendix 2 Belgium: Mosan and Tournai Fonts}}

===Lost===
Formerly complete Tournai fonts, now lost, were at the following locations: Gallaix; Neuf-Berquin; St Venant; and Vimy.  At Stalhille, a recorded base is lost, as are fragments at Binche, Spiennes, and Spiere.{{sfn|Drake (2010), Appendix 2 Belgium: Mosan and Tournai Fonts}}  St Venant, destroyed in World War I, had the most complete cycle of the [[Passion of Christ]] known on any Romanesque font.{{sfn|Drake (2010), p. 9, note 20}} 

